s":[{"name":"Cook","meanings":["English: occupational name for a cook, a seller of cooked meats, or a keeper of an eating house, from Middle English <i>cok</i>, <i>coke</i>, <i>cook</i>, <i>couk</i>, <i>cuk(e)</i> (Old English <i>cōc</i>) ‘cook’ or ‘seller of cooked foods’. See also   Kew  .","Irish and Scottish: usually identical in origin with the English name (see 1 above), but in some cases a shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Cúg</b> ‘son of Hugo’ (see   McCook  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames meaning ‘cook’, such as German and Jewish   Koch  , Dutch   Kook  , Polish <b>Kucharz</b> and   Kucharczyk  , Slovenian and Croatian   Kuhar  , North German   Kuk  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Cooke was born in 1450, in Wickham, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom. He married Elinor Barbor on 20 September 1575, in Bishopwearmouth, Durham, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in Rustington, Sussex, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1450–":"1450–Surnud","1455–Female":"1455–Surnud","1480–1578":"1480–1578","1450–Male":"1450–Surnud","1578":"1578","1455":"1455","1450":"1450","1480":"1480","20 September 1575":"20. september 1575","Bishopwearmouth, Durham, England":"Bishopwearmouth, Durham, England","Wickham, Berkshire, England":"Wickham, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Rustington, Sussex, England":"Rustington, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1450–":"1450–Kuollut",